[1] Viet Nam
Date: Thu, 10 Nov 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 10 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/HAN67722.htm>

Vietnam, the country worst hit by bird flu, reported 2 new outbreaks
this week with more than 1300 fowl killed as the government boosted
efforts to detect the H5N1 virus early.
An Agriculture Ministry report seen on Thursday said 300 ducks died
in the central province of Quang Nam, and animal health workers
slaughtered another 1000 while tests for bird flu, which experts fear
could trigger a human pandemic, were still underway.
It said 15 ducks died on Tuesday [8 Nov 2005] in the northern
province of Bac Giang, where more than 134 000 chickens, ducks and
geese were slaughtered last week during its 1st outbreak this winter.
Agriculture Minister Cao Duc Phat urged local authorities to provide
more information on the epidemic to farmers to help detect outbreaks
quickly.
"Poultry slaughtering should be centralised so the animal health work
can be done better," Phat said on state-run Voice of Vietnam radio.
Around 30 million ducks, or 60 percent of Vietnam's waterfowl, carry
the H5 component of the virus, Phat has said. [Is this information
based upon serology? - Mod.AS]
On Monday [7 Nov 2005], all 3 of Vietnam's deputy prime ministers and
6 ministers started touring different areas in a 2-week campaign to
shake up [energize? set up?] prevention plans and preparations for a
pandemic.
Since bird flu arrived in December 2003, 92 people in Vietnam are
known to have caught the virus and 42 have died, fanning the fears of
experts that the virus could mutate into a form passed easily between
people, which it cannot now.
The latest Vietnamese bird flu victim was a 35-year-old man in Hanoi
who died in late October 2005. But a suspected case, that of a
24-year-old woman from Bac Giang province, turned out to be a false
alarm, Pham Ngoc Dinh, deputy head of the National Hygiene and
Epidemiology Institute, was quoted on Thursday as saying by state
media. [Map at
<http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f0/VietnameseProvincesMap.png>]
