[3] Kuwait - 2 suspected birds
Date: Thu, 10 Nov 2005
From: Nati Elkin <nati@poultrymed.com>
Source: ADN Kronos International, 10 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.adnki.com/index_2Level.php?cat=Trends&loid=8.0.227267884&par=>

2 cases of bird flu have been detected in Kuwait, officials said on
Thursday [10 Nov 2005]. They are the 1st cases of the disease
announced in the Gulf region. The 1st case is said to have come from
a bird imported into Kuwait and was discovered at the airport, while
the 2nd was in what is believed to be a migrating wild fowl found on
a beach. Both diseased birds have been killed. It is not yet known if
they had the H5N1 strain of the virus, which can be fatal for humans.
"The expertise of our authorities has prevented 2 incidents (of bird
flu) in Kuwait," said Sheikh Fahd al-Salem al Sabah, head of Kuwait's
Public Authority for Agriculture and Fisheries (PAAAFR).
He assured reporters that the situation was dealt with quickly and
the bird flu was therefore not allowed spread. He also said that no
humans in Kuwait had the disease.
Only on Tuesday [8 Nov 2005] the director of the Kuwaiti Health
Ministry's Public Health Department, Dr Rashed Al Owaish, told a
conference in Geneva sponsored by the World Health Organization that
the emirate was ready to face any outbreak of bird flu.
He said Kuwait was taking the threat the disease posed seriously and
the cabinet had allocated 5.4 million Kuwaiti dinars (almost 18.5
million US dollars) for the purchase of vaccines, with the 1st
shipment due to arrive in late December 2005.
At the end of the 3-day conference on Wednesday [9 Nov 2005]
delegates outlined a 6-point global action plan, ranging from curbing
the virus in birds to enhanced detection to funding for countries at
risk.
The current H5N1 virus, linked to widespread poultry outbreaks which
began almost 2 years ago in Vietnam and Thailand, has only infected
125 humans so far, killing 64 of them, but health experts have warned
that the virus could evolve into a global human influenza pandemic if
it mutates into a form which could transmit easily among people.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Hopefully, this is a false alert. The identity of the imported bird
and its origin, of the suspected migratory bird, and results of the
tests performed, particularly the data of the virus strain -- in
case confirmed -- will be appreciated. - Mod.AS]
